{{SupportPage|vendor=D-Link|model=TM-G5240}} "8WRGG11..0B1G" and a date code of '''0718''' (May 2007) is silkscreened on the board. The default SSID appears to be '''@HomeXXXX''' where '''XXXX''' has no obvious connection to the unit MAC addresses. WiGLE data seems to indicate this is standard for the D-Link units. A sample SSID for these units is '''@HomeEC22'''. The power adapter included with the device appears to be a '''Jentec''' AF1205-B (5V, 2A). ==Relevant links== *[http://www.devttys0.com/2013/10/reverse-engineering-a-d-link-backdoor/ '''''Reverse Engineering a D-Link Backdoor''''' on '''/dev/ttyS0'''] :It would appear that using a user agent string of ''xmlset_'''roodkcab'''leoj28840ybtide'' will likely grant backdoor access to the web configuration interface.
